iewjournal.com/opinion/editorials/editorial-rj-editorial-board-endorses-marco-rubio-nevada-republican-caucus|title=EDITORIAL: RJ editorial board endorses Marco Rubio for Nevada Republican caucus|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=February 5, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Lowell Sun]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lowellsun.com/breakingnews/ci_29483678/endorsement-rubio-gops-best-chance-reclaim-white-house|title=Endorsement: Rubio GOP's best chance to reclaim White House|work=The Lowell Sun|date=February 6, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[Boston Herald]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/opinion/editorials/2016/02/mass_and_nation_are_ready_for_rubio|title=Mass., and nation, are ready for Rubio|work=Boston Herald|date=February 22, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Republican (Springfield, Massachusetts)|The Republican]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.masslive.com/opinion/index.ssf/2016/02/the_republican_endorses_marco.html|title=The Republican endorses Marco Rubio in March 1 GOP primary: Editorial|work=The Republican|date=February 24, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[San Antonio Express-News]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/opinion/editorials/article/Rubio-best-suited-for-GOP-nomination-6852670.php|title=Rubio best suited for GOP nomination|work=San Antonio Express-News|date=February 24, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.star-telegram.com/opinion/editorials/article62421677.html|title=For the Republican primary, Rubio offers greatest hope|work=Fort Worth Star-Telegram|date=February 25, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[Arkansas Democrat-Gazette]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2016/feb/26/for-marco-rubio-20160226/?f=opinion|title=EDITORIAL: For Marco Rubio|work=Arkansas Democrat-Gazette|date=February 26, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[Star Tribune]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/endorsement-marco-rubio-who-s-energetic-optimistic-and-electable/370333671/|title=Endorsement: Marco Rubio, who's energetic, optimistic and electable|work=Star Tribune|date=February 26, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[Pensacola News Journal]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pnj.com/story/opinion/2016/02/27/editorial-vote-rubio-march/81037370/#pq=5t77YC|title=Editorial: Vote Rubio on March 15|work=Pensacola News Journal|date=February 27, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[Richmond Times-Dispatch]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.richmond.com/opinion/our-opinion/editorial-cartoons/article_26748f78-3d07-500e-a7ac-e53f4312021c.html|title=Rubio for president: Now's your last chance|work=Richmond Times-Dispatch|date=February 27, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[Chattanooga Times Free Press]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/opinion/freepress/story/2016/feb/28/cooper-rubio-best-choice-gop/352036/|title=Chattanooga Free Press announces its endorsement for president|work=Chattanooga Times Free Press|date=February 28, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[Savannah Morning News]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://savannahnow.com/opinion/2016-02-28/georgia-gop-primary-support-marco-rubio#|title=Georgia GOP primary: Support Marco Rubio|date=February 28, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Tampa Tribune]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tbo.com/list/news-opinion-editorials/editorial-rubio-in-gop-primary-20160228/|title=Tampa Tribune editorial: Rubio in Florida GOP primary|date=February 28, 2016|access-date=March 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402073850/http://www.tbo.com/list/news-opinion-editorials/editorial-rubio-in-gop-primary-20160228/|archive-date=April 2, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* ''[[Miami Herald]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/opinion/editorials/article63677042.html|title=In Florida primary: Marco Rubio best candidate to unite GOP|work=Miami Herald|date=March 2, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/opinion/os-ed-gop-presidential-endorsement-20160304-story.html|title=Marco Rubio is GOP's last, best hope: Sentinel Editorial Board|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=March 4, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[Kane County Chronicle]]''<ref>{{cite news |author1=Shaw Media |title=Endorsement: President (R): Rubio |url=http://www.kcchronicle.com/2016/03/01/endorsement-president-r-rubio/ar5lum5/ |accessdate=2016-03-05 |work=[[Kane County Chronicle]] |date=2016-03-04 |location=St. Charles, Ill.|author1-link=Shaw Media }}</ref>\n* ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/opinion/editorial-marco-rubio-can-help-heal-and-unify-the-republican/article_2fb567bb-ecb4-5ebf-a152-5806e7e7f283.html|title=Editorial: Marco Rubio can help heal and unify the Republican Party|work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|date=March 5, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[Northwest Herald]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nwherald.com/2016/02/28/our-view-marco-rubio-for-u-s-president-republican-nomination/abfo26d/|title=Our View: Marco Rubio for U.S. president Republican nomination|work=Northwest Herald|date=March 6, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/opinion/editorials/ct-marco-rubio-tribune-endorsement-clinton-sanders-0310-md-20160309-story.html|title=Marco Rubio for the GOP, but no endorsement for either Democrat|work=Chicago Tribune|date=March 9, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n;Celebrities, commentators, and activists\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Rick Harrison]], pawnbroker, ''[[Pawn Stars]]'' on [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History]]<ref>{{cite web|title = Why does Pawn Stars' Rick Harrison support Marco?|url = https://marcorubio.com/news/pawn-stars-rick-harrison-marco-rubio-cares-about-people/|accessdate = 2015-05-22}}</ref>\n* [[Chris Bravacos]], strategist and bundler<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/presidential-races/199659-waiting-for-jeb|title=Waiting for Jeb|work=The Hill|date=2014-03-03|access-date=2015-12-17}}</ref>\n* [[Babyface (musician)|Babyface]], singer-songwriter<ref name=\"onpolitics.usatoday.com\">{{cite web|url=http://onpolitics.usatoday.com/2015/10/20/hollywood-celebrity-campaign-donations/|title=OnPolitics: Hollywood A-listers flock to Clinton's campaign|work=USA Today}}</ref>\n* [[Niall Ferguson]], historian and fellow of the [[Hoover Institute]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/opinion/2016/02/06/can-rubio-win-wacky-races/Ss9tqrXkma7R2y3t5qWYkL/story.html|title=Can Rubio win the wacky races?|author=Niall Ferguson|newspaper=Boston Globe|date=2016-02-06}}</ref>\n* [[Mark Teixeira]], [[Major League Baseball]] player for the [[New York Yankees]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/tipsheets/morning-money/2015/11/pro-morning-money-211483|title=Mark Teixeira, Tom Farley raising for Rubio|work=Politico}}</ref>\n* [[Johnny Van Zant]], lead singer of [[Lynyrd Skynyrd]]<ref name=\"onpolitics.usatoday.com\"/>\n* [[Anthony Ribustello]], actor and Republican activist<ref name=\"marcony\"/>\n* [[Robert B. Asher|Bob Asher]], Pennsylvania member of [[Republican National Committee]]<ref name=\"marcopa\"/>\n* [[Wayne Grudem]], evangelical theologian, seminary professor, and author<ref>{{cite web|url=https://marcorubio.com/news/wayne-grudem-endorses-marco-rubio/|title=Evangelical Theologian Wayne Grudem Backs Marco|date=January 13, 2016|access-date=March 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160317151302/https://marcorubio.com/news/wayne-grudem-endorses-marco-rubio/|archive-date=March 17, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[John Stephen (New Hampshire)|John Stephen]], 2010 NH GOP gubernatorial nominee<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wmur.com/politics/2010-gop-gubernatorial-nominee-john-stephen-endorses-marco-rubio/37449494|title=2010 GOP gubernatorial nominee John Stephen endorses Marco Rubio|date=January 15, 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Michele Tafoya]], sportscaster<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/MarcoRubioForAmerica/photos/a.705029862946828.1073741825.291970710919414/851232411659905/?type=3&theater |title=Timeline Photos - Marco Rubio For America |publisher=Facebook |date=2016-01-25 |accessdate=2016-02-03}}</ref>\n* [[David Thul]], Iraq War veteran and Republican activist<ref name=\"marcomn\"/>\n* [[Kurt Angle]], professional wrestler<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/in-the-know/in-the-know/267271-pro-wrestler-kurt-angle-goes-to-the-mat-for-rubio|title=Pro wrestler Kurt Angle goes to the mat for Rubio|date=January 27, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Joni Eareckson Tada]], disabilities advocate, Christian author and founder of the global ministry ''Joni and Friends''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldmag.com/2016/02/ballot_boxing_joni_eareckson_tada_endorses_marco_rubio|title=Ballot Boxing: Joni Eareckson Tada endorses Marco Rubio|date=February 4, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Donnie Wahlberg]], actor and member of New Kids on the Block<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/02/21/politics/donnie-wahlberg-marco-rubio/|title=Donnie Wahlberg thinks Marco Rubio has the right stuff|date=February 21, 2016}}</ref> (previously endorsed Carly Fiorina)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/names/2016/02/09/donnie-wahlberg-has-high-expectations-for-carly-fiorina/2UpOR7M7NVUyVGNP9ApMSM/story.html |title=Donnie Wahlberg has high expectations for Carly Fiorina |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=2016-02-09 |accessdate=2016-02-24}}</ref>\n* [[Abby Johnson (activist)|Abby Johnson]], pro-life activist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lifenews.com/2016/02/09/pro-life-advocate-abby-johnson-endorses-marco-rubio-for-president/|title=Pro-Life Advocate Abby Johnson Endorses Marco Rubio for President|date=February 9, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{hidden end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Politics|United States}}\n* [[Political positions of Marco Rubio]]\n* [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016]] \n* [[Republican Party presidential candidates, 2016]]\n* [[Republican Party presidential debates, 2016]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FtZLnpW7FX4 Marco Rubio video released prior to official Presidential announcement]\n* [http://www.marcorubio.com Official Marco Rubio campaign website]\n* [http://www.c-span.org/video/?325251-1/live-monday-530-pm-et-senator-marco-rubio-rfl-presidential-campaign-announcement C-SPAN coverage of Rubio's campaign announcement]\n\n{{United States presidential election, 2016}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rubio, Marco}}\n[[Category:2016 United States Republican Party presidential campaigns]]\n[[Category:Marco Rubio]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox U.S. federal election campaign\n | committee        = Marco Rubio for President\n | logo             = [[File:Marcorubio.svg|275px]]\n | campaign         = [[2016 United States presidential election|U.S. presidential election, 2016]]\n | candidate        = [[Marco Rubio]]<br /><small>[[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] (2011\u2013present)<br/>[[Speaker of the Florida House of Representatives]] (2007\u20132009)</small>\n | cand_id          = P60006723\n | fec_date         = 2016-6-30<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/pres16/candidate.php?id=N00030612|accessdate=October 14, 2016}}</ref>\n | status           = Announced: April 13, 2015<br> Suspended: March 15, 2016\n | affiliation      = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]\n | headquarters     = P.O. Box 558701<br>[[Miami, Florida]], U.S.\n | key_people       = [[Terry Sullivan (political consultant)|Terry Sullivan]] (Campaign Manager), [[Alex Conant]] (Communications Director)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://marcorubio.com/news/marco-rubio-strategy-super-saturday/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-03-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307080559/https://marcorubio.com/news/marco-rubio-strategy-super-saturday/ |archivedate=2016-03-07 }}</ref>\n | receipts         = 51,747,005\n | slogan           = A New American Century\n | chant            = Mar-co!\n | homepage         = [https://marcorubio.com/ www.marcorubio.com]\n}}\nThe '''2016 presidential campaign of [[Marco Rubio]]''', who is currently the senior [[United States Senate|United States senator]] from [[Florida]], was formally announced on April 13, 2015, at an event at the [[Freedom Tower (Miami)|Freedom Tower]] in Downtown Miami.<ref name=\"He's in\">Jaffe, Alexandra; [[Dana Bash|Bash, Dana]] (April 13, 2015) [http://www.cnn.com/2015/04/13/politics/election-2016-marco-rubio-presidential-campaign/ \"He's in: Marco Rubio announces presidential bid\"], [[CNN]]. Retrieved April 14, 2015.</ref>  Early polling showed Rubio, who was considered a potential candidate for [[Vice-President of the United States|Vice President]] by Republican presidential nominee [[Mitt Romney]] in [[2012 United States presidential election|2012]],  as a frontrunner candidate for the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016|Republican nomination]] for [[president of the United States]] in [[2016 United States presidential election|2016]] since at least the end of the 2012 election.<ref name=\"Pitch\">Nelson, Rebecca (April 13, 2015) [http://www.nationaljournal.com/2016-elections/marco-rubio-presidential-announcement-2016-20150413 \"Marco Rubio Makes His Pitch as the Fresh Face of the GOP in 2016\"], ''[[National Journal]]''. Retrieved April 14, 2015.</ref> Rubio was the second [[Cuban American]] to run for [[president of the United States]], with Republican [[Ted Cruz]] announcing his campaign three weeks earlier. He suspended his campaign on March 15, 2016, after finishing second in Florida's primary.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Peters|first1=Jeremy|last2=Barbaro|first2=Michael|title=Marco Rubio Suspends His Presidential Campaign|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/16/us/politics/marco-rubio.html?_r=0|accessdate=16 March 2016|date=16 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\n===2012 presidential election===\n{{Further|Republican Party vice presidential candidate selection, 2012}}\n[[File:Marco Rubio by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|thumb|right|Senator Marco Rubio speaking at the 2014 [[Conservative Political Action Conference]]]]\nAs early as January 2011, there had been speculation that he might seek the office of the president or vice-president. In January 2011, Rubio stated he had no interest in being the vice-presidential candidate in the [[2012 United States presidential election|2012 presidential election]].<ref>{{cite web|first1=Michael|last1=O'Brien|accessdate=2019-08-27|title=Rubio rejects running as Republicans' VP nominee|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/136955-rubio-rejects-running-as-republicans-vp-nominee|date=10 January 2011|website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]}}</ref> Despite his comments, speculation continued that presidential candidate [[Mitt Romney]] might select Rubio as his running mate.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Roig-Fanzia|first1=Manuel|title=Marco Rubio's compelling family story embellishes facts, documents show|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/marco-rubios-compelling-family-story-embellishes-facts-documents-show/2011/10/20/gIQAaVHD1L_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=October 20, 2011}}</ref> According to the book ''[[Double Down: Game Change 2012|Double Down]]'', Romney's campaign narrowed down his list of potential nominees for vice president to five candidates, one of which was Rubio.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sean Sullivan and Philip Rucker |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/obamas-advisers-considered-replacing-biden-with-clinton-according-to-book/2013/10/31/2f8bbf10-4285-11e3-8b74-d89d714ca4dd_story.html |title=Obama's advisers considered replacing Biden with Clinton, according to book |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=October 31, 2013 |accessdate=November 1, 2013}}</ref> However, Romney ultimately picked [[Wisconsin]] congressman [[Paul Ryan]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rucker|first1=Phillip|last2=Helderman|first2=Rosalind S.|title=Politics Paul Ryan is Romney's VP pick, setting up stark choice on budget issues|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/paul-ryan-is-romneys-pick-for-vice-presidential-nominee/2012/08/11/dc2f5070-e0f1-11e1-8fc5-a7dcf1fc161d_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=August 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2016 presidential election===\n\nThroughout 2014, groups had been raising money to support a potential Rubio presidential campaign. Groups supporting Rubio raised over $530,000 in the first three months of 2014, most of which was spent on consultants and data analytics, in what was seen as preparations for a presidential campaign.<ref>{{cite news|title=Paul, Rubio lead potential Republican 2016 contenders in spending|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2014-04-16/news/sns-rt-us-usa-campaign-money-20140416_1_ron-paul-marco-rubio-state-hillary-clinton|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=April 20, 2014|date=April 16, 2014}}</ref>\n \nEarly polling data showed Rubio as a frontrunner for the nomination shortly after the 2012 election. From late 2012 to mid-2013, Rubio came in first in eight consecutive [[Nationwide opinion polling for the Republican Party 2016 presidential primaries|national polls]] among potential 2016 candidates, from such sources as [[Public Policy Polling]], [[Harper Polling]], [[Quinnipiac University Polling Institute|Quinnipiac University]], and [[Farleigh Dickinson University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publicpolicypolling.com/pdf/2011/PPP_Release_National_1206.pdf |title=Clinton, Rubio 2016? |publisher=Publicpolicypolling.com |accessdate=2015-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.harperpolling.com/polls/national-poll-of-republicans|title=National Poll of Republicans|work=Harper Polling|access-date=2015-04-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123231622/http://www.harperpolling.com/polls/national-poll-of-republicans|archive-date=2015-01-23|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publicpolicypolling.com/pdf/2011/PPP_Release_National_011013.pdf |title=Clinton could be hard to beat if she runs in 2016 |publisher=Publicpolicypolling.com |accessdate=2015-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publicpolicypolling.com/pdf/2011/PPP_Release_National_207.pdf |title=Clinton, Rubio lead primary contests |publisher=Publicpolicypolling.com |accessdate=2015-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publicpolicypolling.com/pdf/2011/PPP_Release_4313.pdf |title=Hillary Takes It All |publisher=Publicpolicypolling.com |accessdate=2015-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quinnipiac.edu/news-and-events/quinnipiac-university-poll/national/release-detail?ReleaseID=1876|title=April 3, 2013 - Early Look At 2016 GOP Field Shows 5-Way Horse Race, Quinnipiac University National Poll Finds; New Jersey's Christie Has Just 14%|work=Quinnipiac University}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://publicmind.fdu.edu/2013/hillary/|title=Hillary Clinton Leads 2016 Democratic Hopefuls; No Clear Frontrunner for GOP|work=Fairleigh Dickinson University}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publicpolicypolling.com/pdf/2011/PPP_Release_National_515Final.pdf |title=Democrats still behind Clinton, 4 way race for Republicans |publisher=Publicpolicypolling.com |accessdate=2015-04-17}}</ref> In [[Statewide opinion polling for the Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016|statewide polls]], he had performed most prominently in his home state of Florida, alongside Jeb Bush,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publicpolicypolling.com/pdf/2011/PPP_Release_FL_9512.pdf |title=Rubio, Clinton early 2016 leaders in Florida |publisher=Publicpolicypolling.com |accessdate=2015-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publicpolicypolling.com/pdf/2011/PPP_Release_FL_011713.pdf |title=Clinton could beat Bush and Rubio in Florida in 2016 |publisher=Publicpolicypolling.com |accessdate=2015-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publicpolicypolling.com/pdf/2011/PPP_Release_FL_032113.pdf |title=Clinton's popularity soars in Florida while Rubio stumbles |publisher=Publicpolicypolling.com |accessdate=2015-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publicpolicypolling.com/pdf/2014/PPP_Release_FL_611.pdf |title=Bush leads Republicans, Neck and Neck with Clinton |publisher=Publicpolicypolling.com |accessdate=2015-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quinnipiac.edu/news-and-events/quinnipiac-university-poll/florida/release-detail?ReleaseID=2063|title=July 24, 2014 - Obama In Slump, But Clinton Scores In Florida, Quinnipiac University Poll Finds; Rubio Narrows GOP Gap As Jeb Bush Sags|work=Quinnipiac University|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729225437/http://www.quinnipiac.edu/news-and-events/quinnipiac-university-poll/florida/release-detail?ReleaseID=2063|archivedate=July 29, 2014}}</ref> and has also performed fairly well in [[Suffolk University]] polls in such states as [[Colorado]], [[Michigan]], and [[Minnesota]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suffolk.edu/documents/SUPRC/9_17_2014_marginals.pdf |title=Final Colorado Toplines |publisher=Suffolk.edu |accessdate=2015-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suffolk.edu/documents/SUPRC/marginals_9_11_2014.pdf |title=Final Michigan Toplines |publisher=Suffolk.edu |accessdate=2015-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suffolk.edu/documents/SUPRC/4_29_2014_marginals.pdf |title=Minnesota Likely Voters |publisher=Suffolk.edu |accessdate=2015-04-17}}</ref> A poll from the [[WMUR-TV|WMUR]]/University, tracking New Hampshire Republican primary voters' sentiment, showed Rubio at the top alongside [[Kentucky]] senator [[Rand Paul]] in March 2013. However, he had dropped to 10th place behind other Republican contenders by April 2014. The poll, however, also suggested that Rubio was not disliked by primary voters, which could have been positive for him had other candidates chosen not to run.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Marco Rubio's long, hard fall in New Hampshire|url=http://washingtonexaminer.com/marco-rubios-long-hard-fall-in-new-hampshire/article/2547467|magazine=The Washington Examiner|accessdate=April 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=THE WMUR GRANITE STATE POLL THE UNIVERSITY OF NEW HAMPSHIRE|url=http://cola.unh.edu/sites/cola.unh.edu/files/research_publications/gsp2014_spring_primary041814.pdf|publisher=WMUR/University}}</ref> By the time of Rubio's announcement, he had regained some standing in the polls. A March 2015 NBC/Wall Street Journal poll asked Republican Party voters if they could see themselves supporting the various candidates. Rubio won the poll with 56 percent of Republican voters saying they could see themselves supporting Rubio, while only 26 percent said they could not. Wisconsin governor [[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]] and former Arkansas governor [[Mike Huckabee]] trailed just behind Rubio with 53 and 52 percent, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nelson|first1=Louis|title=Good news for Marco Rubio in GOP poll |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/03/good-news-for-marco-rubio-in-gop-poll-116081.html|publisher=Politico|date=March 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=2016 Blues? 57% of Republicans Can't Support Chris Christie|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2015/03/11/2016-blues-57-of-republicans-cant-support-chris-christie/|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|date=March 11, 2015}}</ref> A CNN/ORC poll conducted from March 13 to March 15, 2015, found that Rubio was tied with [[Chris Christie]] for the Republican nomination.<ref>{{cite news|title=CNN/ORC Poll|url=http://i2.cdn.turner.com/cnn/2015/images/03/17/poll.2016.pdf|publisher=CNN/ORC|date=March 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, Rubio began laying the foundation for a presidential campaign. He began contacting top donors and appointed advisors, including [[George Edward Seay III|George Seay]], who previously worked on [[Rick Perry|Rick Perry's]] [[Rick Perry presidential campaign, 2012|2012 presidential campaign]] and [[Mitt Romney|Mitt Romney's]] [[Mitt Romney presidential campaign, 2008|2008 presidential campaign]], and Jim Rubright, who had previously worked for [[Jeb Bush]], Romney, and [[John McCain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2015/01/23/rubio-signs-on-top-fundraiser-lines-up-donors-in-move-toward-2016-bid/|title=Rubio signs on top fundraiser, lines up donors in move toward 2016 bid|work=Fox News}}</ref><ref name=Murray>{{cite web | url=http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/elections/marco-rubio-takes-steps-towards-2016-run-n292031 | title=Marco Rubio Takes Steps Towards 2016 Run | work=NBC News | date=January 23, 2015 | accessdate=January 24, 2015 | author=Murray, Mark}}</ref> Rubio also instructed his aides to \"prepare for a presidential campaign\" prior to a Team Marco 2016 fundraising meeting in [[South Beach]].<ref name=Caputo>{{cite web | url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/state/florida/article8013126.html | title=Sen. Marco Rubio to aides: 'Prepare for a presidential campaign' | work=[[Miami Herald]] | date=January 23, 2015 | accessdate=January 24, 2015 | author=Caputo, Marc}}</ref>\n\n==Campaign==\n{{see also|Nationwide opinion polling for the Republican Party 2016 presidential primaries|Nationwide opinion polling for the United States presidential election, 2016}}\n[[File:Senator of Florida Marco Rubio at Marco Rubio at the Derry-Salem Elks Lodge in Salem NH by Michael Vadon 01.jpg|thumb|right|Rubio speaking to voters in [[Salem, New Hampshire]].]]\n[[File:Marco Rubio by Gage Skidmore 6.jpg|right|thumb|Rubio speaking at an event hosted by the [[Republican Party of Iowa|Iowa Republican Party]] in October 2015.]]\nOn March 30, 2015, Rubio announced on [[Fox News]] and through social media that he would be making a \"big announcement\" on April 13 in [[Miami, Florida]]. While he did not specify whether the announcement pertained to his [[United States Senate election in Florida, 2016|reelection as a United States Senator]] or for the Presidency, most media consensus was that Rubio would be announcing his presidential run. He made the announcement at the [[Freedom Tower (Miami)|Freedom Tower]] in Downtown Miami.<ref name=\"He's in\"/><ref name=\"Pitch\"/> In his announcement speech, Rubio cast himself as forward-looking and a leader for a new generation of Americans, in contrast to Democrat [[Hillary Clinton]], who announced her presidential campaign the day before; in addition, he announced he would not seek re-election as senator.<ref name=\"He's in\"/><ref>{{cite news | last1=Leary | first1=Alex | title=Marco Rubio, Casting Himself as a Leader for a New Generation, is Running for President | url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/politics/stateroundup/marco-rubio-will-announce-for-president-today-in-miami/2225233 | date=April 13, 2015 | newspaper=[[Tampa Bay Times]] | accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref> With the announcement, Rubio became [[2016 United States presidential election#Major party candidates|the fourth major candidate to officially announce a run]] after Republicans (and fellow senators) [[Ted Cruz]] of [[Texas]] and [[Rand Paul]] of [[Kentucky]] and Democrat Hillary Clinton.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jaffe|first1=Alexandra|title=Rubio confirms April 13 announcement in Miami|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/03/28/politics/rubio-announcement-april/|publisher=CNN|date=March 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lippman|first1=Daniel|title=Hillary Clinton threatens to steal Marco Rubio's thunder  |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/04/hillary-threatens-to-steal-rubios-thunder-116870.html|publisher=Politico|date=April 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Rubio initially struggled to poll as well as other frontrunners such as [[Chris Christie]], [[Jeb Bush]], [[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]], and [[Donald Trump]], Rubio's performance in [[Republican Party presidential debates, 2016|the debates]] was widely seen as a boosting factor in his rising poll numbers in the late summer and fall of 2015. Over the course of both of the first two debates, in August and September, Rubio was widely praised as one of the top performers, even being called the winner by some analysts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/media/gop-republican-debate-august-2015-highlights-analysis|title=GOP debate: Trump, Bush, Cruz, Paul, and Rubio mix it up|work=CBS News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2015-08-07/why-marco-rubio-may-have-won-the-first-republican-debate|title=Why Marco Rubio May Have Won the First Republican Debate|work=Bloomberg}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/matt-teitelbaum/marco-rubio-shines-at-second-debate_b_8156362.html|title=Marco Rubio Shines at Second Debate|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://insider.foxnews.com/2015/09/16/charles-krauthammer-carly-fiorina-won-gop-debate-marco-rubio-came-close-second|title=Krauthammer: Fiorina won GOP Debate, Rubio Came in Close Second|work=Fox News|accessdate=September 23, 2015|date=2015-09-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/09/17/politics/republican-debate-winners-losers-donald-trump/|title=Republican Debate: Winners and Losers|work=CNN Politics|accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/424236/GOP-debate-fiorina-rubio-won-trump-kasich-lost|title=GOP Debate: Fiorina, Rubio Won; Trump, Kasich Lost|work=National Review|accessdate=September 23, 2015|date=2015-09-18}}</ref> As a result, Rubio's poll numbers began to increase once more, and he eventually reached the #3 position in most polling averages, only behind Trump and [[Ben Carson]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://elections.huffingtonpost.com/pollster/2016-national-gop-primary | work=Huffington Post | title=2016 National Republican Primary \u2013 Polls \u2013 HuffPost Pollster}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2016/president/us/2016_republican_presidential_nomination-3823.html|title=2016 Republican Presidential Nomination|accessdate=September 20, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.270towin.com/2016-republican-nomination/|title=2016 Republican Presidential Nomination|accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref> Another factor that was seen as greatly improving Rubio's chances was the exit from the race of Scott Walker on September 21. Analysts claimed that many of Walker's supporters and donors were turning to him as a viable alternative to Bush, who could also claim broad appeal to both moderates and conservatives. With Walker out of the race, Rubio was widely viewed as the next likeliest candidate who best matched this criteria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2015/09/24/rubio-rising-marco-gets-2016-boost-from-debates-walker-exit/|title=Rubio Rising? Marco gets 2016 Boost from Debates, Walker's Exit|work=Fox News|accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/rubio-benefits-from-walker-exit-1442964452|title=Rubio Benefits from Walker Exit|work=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/marco-rubio-scott-walker-drop-out-2015-9|title=Marco Rubio gains from Scott Walker's drop out|work=Business Insider|accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref> The Rubio campaign was even reported as hiring up to nine of Walker's former top staffers less than 24 hours after his exit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/politics/2015/09/23/rubio-is-picking-up-spoils-walker-campaign/|title=Marco Rubio is picking up the spoils of Scott Walker's defunct campaign|work=Fox News Latino|accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Matt Lewis (journalist)|Matt Lewis]] has commented that, \"Democrats should fear Marco Rubio\", who Lewis saw as  \"heralding a generational shift\" for Republicans.<ref name=Lewis103115>Matt K. Lewis - [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/republicans/11967729/Geriatric-Democrats-should-fear-Marco-Rubio-and-the-Republican-youth-wing.html \"Geriatric Democrats should fear Marco Rubio and the Republican youth wing; Florida Senator's debate triumph comes as Paul Ryan is elected Speaker, heralding a generational shift that conservaties must seize\"], ''The Telegraph'', October 31, 2015. Retrieved 2015-11-02</ref> Rubio, along with [[Paul Ryan]] and his recent ascension to the [[House speaker|House speakership]], Lewis says, means \"both men will be attacked for their youth and energy\", adding: \"But it\u2019s hard to look at this strong and diverse Republican bench, and not juxtapose it to the Democrats, whose party \u2013 now that [[Barack Obama]] is a [[Lame duck (politics)|lame duck]] \u2013 seems to be represented by a bunch of old white people, such as [[Hillary Clinton]], 68, [[Bernie Sanders]], the 74-year-old democratic socialist candidate, ...[[Nancy Pelosi]], 75, and [[Harry Reid]], 75... For Democrats, who were hoping they would get to deal with old [[politician|pols]] like [[John Boehner]] and [[Jeb Bush]]...the world just got a little bit scarier\".<ref name=Lewis103115/>\n\nThe [[November 2015 Paris attacks]] were widely seen as altering the narrative of the 2016 presidential primaries,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2015-11-16/paris-terrorist-attacks-could-mark-a-turning-point-in-the-republican-primary|title=Paris Attacks Could Mark Turning Point in Republican Race|work=Bloomberg|accessdate=December 2, 2015}}</ref> and in particular gave a boost to Rubio for his foreign policy stances, in comparison to such candidates who were softer on foreign policy such as Carson, and also for his having political experience, in contrast to other front-runners such as Trump.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/paris-massacre-could-alter-the-2016-presidential-race-in-this-country/2015/11/14/0ae2f22c-8b04-11e5-9a07-453018f9a0ec_story.html|title=Paris massacre could alter the 2016 presidential race in this country|work=Washington Post|accessdate=November 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Marco Rubio (24556513751).jpg|thumb|left|Rubio speaking with supporters at a campaign rally featuring U.S. Senator [[Joni Ernst]] at the Forte Banquet Center in Des Moines, Iowa in January 2016.]]\n\nDuring the latter part of 2015, Rubio's voting record in the senate came under scrutiny. Jeb Bush, during the [[CNBC]] debate on October 28, told Rubio that he could either campaign or resign, Rubio responding that Bush had not made similar comments about the voting record of [[John McCain]] during his 2008 presidential campaign and concluded that Bush was only criticizing \"because we're running for the same position and someone has convinced you that attacking me is going to help you.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/258475-bush-rubio-spar-over-rubios-missed-votes|title=Bush, Rubio spar over Rubio's missed votes|newspaper=The Hill|date=October 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/4091922/republican-debate-marco-rubio-jeb-bush/|title=Marco Rubio and Jeb Bush Trade Insults Over Missing Votes|magazine=TIME|date=October 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/marco-rubio-jeb-bush-gop-debate_us_56316cd7e4b00aa54a4cb4d2|title=Marco Rubio Turns Attacks On His Senate Absenteeism Back On Jeb Bush|date=October 28, 2015|work=Huffington Post}}</ref> In December, while in [[Iowa]], fellow presidential candidate [[Chris Christie]] mentioned Rubio missing a vote on a national spending bill the senator opposed and added, \"Just show up to work and vote no, and like if you don't want to, then quit.\" On December 29, Rubio responded to Christie by claiming to have close to a 90% attendance record while also retorting that the governor had \"been missing in [[New Jersey]] half of the time.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/presidential/caucus/2015/12/29/christie-jabs-rubio-iowa-voting-record/77991344/|title=Christie jabs Rubio in Iowa on voting record|newspaper=Des Moines Register|date=December 29, 2015}}</ref> In late December, [[Right to Rise]], a Jeb Bush super PAC, released an ad claiming that Rubio had both missed a classified meeting the previous month after the Paris attacks and \"missed more total votes than any other senator\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/bush-super-pac-unveils-ad-slamming-rubios-voting-record/|date=December 29, 2015|publisher=CBS News|title=Bush super PAC unveils ad slamming Rubio's voting record|first=Rebecca|last=Shabad}}</ref> On January 7, Rubio defended his record by arguing that votes were \"precooked\" and votes were used to \"make a statement.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/presidential-races/265101-rubio-most-senate-votes-precooked|title=Rubio defends Senate voting record|date=January 7, 2016|newspaper=The Hill}}</ref>\n\nRubio participated in the January 28 Fox News debate, charging Cruz with building his campaign on \"the lie\" stemming from his stance on immigration and insisting in Jeb Bush's book ''[[Immigration Wars: Forging an American Solution]]'' that the latter changed his \"position on immigration\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/29/us/politics/republican-debate.html?_r=0|title=Ted Cruz and Marco Rubio Clash Harshly, Filling Void on G.O.P. Debate Stage|date=January 28, 2016|newspaper=New York Times}}</ref> January 29, during an interview the following day, Rubio was confident about his chances in Iowa, though did not deny that Ted Cruz was the frontrunner since by Rubio's admission, \"He\u2019s spent basically all of his money in Iowa.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/jan/29/marco-rubio-ted-cruz-would-be-front-runner-iowa/|title=Marco Rubio: Ted Cruz would be the front-runner in Iowa|newspaper=Washington Times|date=January 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Early primaries===\nRubio finished in third place in the [[2016 Iowa Republican caucuses|Iowa caucus]] on February 1. Though polling had shown him in third place prior to the caucus, the result was still treated as a surprisingly strong showing. Amber Phillips of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote of Rubio's performance, \"He over-performed expectations, and for that, Rubio perhaps almost as much as Cruz can call Monday a win.\"<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2016/02/02/marco-rubios-very-big-night-in-iowa/|title=Marco Rubio's very big night in Iowa|first=Amber|last=Phillips}}</ref> After being projected in third place, Rubio said in a speech that he had defied expectations and swore that when he was the nominee of the election cycle, \"we are going to unify this party, and we are going to unify the conservative movement\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/marco-rubio-beat-expectations-iowa-caucuses/story?id=36655652|title=Marco Rubio Says He Beat Expectations In Iowa Caucuses|first=Meridith|last=McGraw|publisher=ABC News}}</ref> A little over a week after the primary, on February 10, Rubio accused Cruz of having misled voters through claiming fellow candidate [[Ben Carson]] would be ending his campaign in what he called \"a concerted effort that I'm sure they planned to execute on something in order to influence the election.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/in-south-carolina-marco-rubio-accuses-ted-cruz-of-iowa-voter-deception/|title=In South Carolina, Marco Rubio accuses Ted Cruz of Iowa voter deception|date=February 10, 2016|first=Reena|last=Flores}}</ref>\n\nGoing into New Hampshire, Rubio by February 5, four days after the Iowa victory, was polling at an average of 16%. This placed him in second place, behind Trump.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fivethirtyeight.com/features/marco-rubio-stole-ted-cruzs-iowa-bounce/|title=Marco Rubio Stole Ted Cruz's Iowa Bounce|work=FiveThirtyEight|date=February 5, 2016}}</ref>\nAt the [[Republican Party presidential debates, 2016#February 6, 2016 \u2013 Goffstown, New Hampshire|New Hampshire debate]] on February 6, 2016, Rubio was criticized by Christie for repeating memorized speeches, to which Rubio replied by repeating four times a statement to the effect that President Obama was destroying America.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/08/us/politics/marco-rubio-comes-back-swinging-after-difficult-debate.html | title=Marco Rubio Comes Back Swinging After Difficult Debate | work=New York Times | date=February 7, 2016 | accessdate=February 7, 2016 | author=Peters, Jeremy W.}}</ref> Rubio defended these remarks the following day, saying with respect to the statement that Obama \"knows exactly what he's doing\" that \"It's what I believe and it's what I'm going to continue to say, because it happens to be one of the main reasons why I am running.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/marco-rubio-defends-repeated-attack-president-obama-republican/story?id=36760445 | title=Marco Rubio Defends Repeated Attack of President Obama During Republican Debate | work=ABC News | date=February 7, 2016 | accessdate=February 7, 2016 | author=De La Cuetara, Ines}}</ref> Rubio came in fifth place during the [[2016 New Hampshire Republican primary|New Hampshire primary]] on February 9. Shortly afterward, Rubio admitted to supporters that he was disappointed and concluded that his debate performance three days prior had not helped him in the state.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/marco-rubio-disappointed-in-new-hampshire-primary-showing/|title=Marco Rubio \"disappointed\" in New Hampshire primary showing|date=February 10, 2016|publisher=CBS News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/marco-rubio-admits-debate-performance-didnt-hampshire/story?id=36840046|title=Marco Rubio Admits Debate Performance 'Didn't Help' Him in New Hampshire|date=February 10, 2016|publisher=ABC News}}</ref> Chris Christie, who came in sixth place behind Rubio, dropped out the following day. Rubio responded to his ended candidacy by praising him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/02/10/politics/marco-rubio-chris-christie-debate-attack/|title=Marco Rubio: Debate attack didn't help Chris Christie|first=Tom|last=LoBianco|date=February 10, 2016|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2016/02/10/marco-rubio-no-hard-feelings-over-christies-debate-tactics/|title=Marco Rubio: No Hard Feelings Over Chris Christie's Debate Tactics|first=Tessa|last=Berenson|publisher=Fortune}}</ref>\n\nCampaigning in South Carolina on February 11, Rubio charged Trump and Bush with having no foreign policy experience and acknowledged [[John Kasich]] as experienced in that regard, but not having been involved with foreign policy \"in a long time.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/02/11/politics/marco-rubio-slams-opponents-in-south-carolina/|title=Marco Rubio slams opponents by name in South Carolina|first=Julia|last=Manchester|publisher=CNN}}</ref> Rubio participated in the February 13 [[CBS News]] debate, exchanging with Cruz over the latter's claim regarding Rubio's comments in Spanish during an appearance on [[Univision]]. Rubio responded by claiming that Cruz did not know how to speak Spanish, Cruz retorting through speaking the language. The following day, February 14, Rubio denied that he was attempting to call into question Cruz's legitimacy as a Latino, instead having meant to question if he understood him and, he added, regarding Cruz, \"He's just going off what other people are telling him, and it's false. It's just not true.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/02/14/politics/marco-rubio-ted-cruz-lies/|title=Marco Rubio accuses Ted Cruz of lying|date=February 14, 2016|publisher=CNN}}</ref> On February 17, [[Governor of South Carolina]] [[Nikki Haley]] endorsed Rubio.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/02/breaking-news-south-carolina-gov-nikki-haley-to-endorse-marco-rubio-219390|title=South Carolina Gov. Nikki Haley endorses Marco Rubio|date=February 17, 2016|publisher=POLITICO}}</ref> Haley's endorsement was seen as helpful to Rubio, exit polls after the primary having one in four voters indicate that they had supported Rubio only after the governor's endorsement.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2016/02/21/how-marco-rubio-edged-out-ted-cruz-for-second-in-s-c-hint-nikki-haley-helped/|title=How Marco Rubio edged out Ted Cruz for second in S.C. (hint: Nikki Haley helped)|newspaper=Washington Post|date=February 21, 2016}}</ref> In the [[2016 South Carolina Republican primary|South Carolina primary]] on February 20, Rubio finished in second place at 22%,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-wins-south-carolina-bush-drops-out-of-gop-race/2016/02/20/16f80c9a-d655-11e5-be55-2cc3c1e4b76b_story.html|title=Trump wins South Carolina; Bush drops out of GOP race|date=February 21, 2016|newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> but won zero delegates from the state.<ref name=NYTdelegates/> Jeb Bush came in fourth place and then suspended his campaign.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/election/article61572637.html|title=Jeb Bush falls as Marco Rubio rises in South Carolina|date=February 20, 2016|newspaper=Miami Herald}}</ref> In his speech afterward, Rubio said the primary had \"become a three person race, and we will win the nomination\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://talkingpointsmemo.com/livewire/rubio-south-carolina-primary-speech|title=After South Carolina Primary, Marco Rubio Declares It A Three-Person Race|date=February 20, 2016|first=Caitlin|last=Macneal}}</ref>\n\nThe next voting state, [[Nevada]], was seen as one that Rubio could potentially claim as his first victory due to the outpouring of support from the Republican Party. Some commentators observed Rubio having spent six years of his childhood in the state as a potential advantage over the other candidates in appealing to voters.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/23/us/politics/marco-rubio-las-vegas.html?_r=0|title=Marco Rubio Bets on Nevada, a State That Shaped His Childhood|date=February 22, 2016|newspaper=New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/feb/17/marco-rubio-nevada-primary-voters-latinos-mormons-sams-town-casino|title=Why Nevada could be the state where Marco Rubio's campaign really takes off|date=February 17, 2016}}</ref> Rubio acknowledged his roots within the state, but believed that he was similar to the other candidates in having to \"compete hard\" for a victory. A poll was released on February 17 showing Rubio in second place at 19%, twenty-six points behind Trump who was at 45%. Nevada lieutenant governor [[Mark Hutchison]] publicly expressed confidence in Rubio's chances, as did the candidate himself.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/02/22/politics/marco-rubio-nevada-caucus-strategy/|title=Marco Rubio's moment of truth in Nevada|date=February 22, 2016|publisher=CNN}}</ref> However, on February 23, the day of the [[2016 Nevada Republican caucuses|primary]], Rubio finished in second place, behind Trump.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-rubio-no-wins-20160224-story.html|title=Marco Rubio's no-win Republican primary strategy can't last|date=February 24, 2016|newspaper=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> The victory widened Trump's lead over the others, leading to a belief that he was going to become the nominee regardless of the results of Super Tuesday. Following the second-place finish, aides of Rubio said he would only win if supporters of both Kasich, who was still running despite poor performances in nearly every one of the four states, and Bush coalesced behind him.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/25/us/politics/marco-rubio.html?_r=0|title=Marco Rubio Gets Party's Blessing, but Not Voters'|date=February 24, 2016|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nRubio participated in the CNN debate on February 25, having heated exchanges with front-runner Donald Trump.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/02/26/politics/republican-debate-recap/index.html|title=Republican presidential debate: 6 takeaways|date=February 25, 2016|publisher=CNN}}</ref> On February 26, Rubio followed up on his performance the previous day at a rally in [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]] by mocking Trump's misspelled tweets and suggested Trump's \"pants were wet\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/02/26/politics/marco-rubio-attacks-donald-trump-wet-pants/|title=Marco Rubio mocks Donald Trump for 'wet' pants|date=February 26, 2016|publisher=CNN}}</ref> Rubio made further comments about Trump which included remarks denouncing his privileged background as having made him unfamiliar with financial difficulties and his physical appearance.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-oe-0228-mcmanus-rubio-20160228-column.html|title=It's Marco Rubio's turn to take Trump down|date=February 28, 2016|newspaper=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/article/marco-rubio-now-copying-trump-insult-strategy|title=Marco Rubio Is Now Matching Donald Trump Insult-for-Insult: 'You Know What They Say About Men With Small Hands'|date=February 29, 2016}}</ref> Weeks later, Rubio regretted mocking Trump in this manner, stating that his \"kids were embarrassed by it\".<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/mar/09/marco-rubio-attacks-donald-trump-regrets-republicans</ref>\n\n=== Super Tuesday; March contests ===\nLeading up to Super Tuesday, there were mixed reactions to how well Rubio would perform.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gawker.com/when-marco-rubio-is-a-super-tuesday-loser-remember-its-1762268528 |publisher=Gawker |date=March 1, 2016 |title=When Marco Rubio Is a Super Tuesday Loser, Remember It's All Going According to Plan |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311072340/http://gawker.com/when-marco-rubio-is-a-super-tuesday-loser-remember-its-1762268528 |archivedate=March 11, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/01/upshot/where-marco-rubio-has-the-best-chance-to-win.html?_r=0|title=Where Marco Rubio Has the Best Chance to Win|first=Nate|last=Cohn|newspaper=New York Times}}</ref> The following day, Rubio withdrew from planned appearances in [[Kentucky]] and [[Louisiana]] that were scheduled in the latter part of the week, leading to speculation that the move was the result of a lack of confidence the Rubio campaign had in its chances to win the two states, polling at the time showing Trump in first place.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/news/politics/elections/kentucky/2016/03/02/rubio-cancels-kentucky-rally/81249430/|title=Marco Rubio cancels Kentucky rally|date=March 3, 2016|publisher=courier-journal.com}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, Rubio had won the [[2016 Puerto Rico Republican primary|Puerto Rico Republican primary]] by a large margin, pulling in 71.02% of the vote. He took all twenty-three delegates.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://presidenciales16.ceepur.org/resumen.aspx.htm | title=CEE - Primarias Presidenciales Republicanas 2016}}</ref> Rubio previously addressed Puerto Rico during a CNN debate, arguing that its problems stemmed from an economy that was not growing and that it was \"too expensive to do business there.\" He also blamed Puerto Rico governor [[Alejandro Garc\u00eda Padilla]] for not cutting government spending, Padilla afterward charging him with being employed by the \"vultures that fund his campaign.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/02/26/news/economy/marco-rubio-puerto-rico-bankruptcy/|title=Marco Rubio: Bankruptcy isn't right for Puerto Rico|date=February 26, 2016|publisher=CNN|first=Heather|last=Long}}</ref> For the March 8 contests offering over 140 delegates, Rubio won one delegate from Hawaii and zero delegates from three other states: Idaho, Michigan and [[2016 Mississippi Republican primary|Mississippi]]. He was third in Hawaii and Idaho, but ranked fourth in Michigan and Mississippi with less than 10% of the vote. This left him with a total of 152 delegates compared to Trump's 459 and Cruz's 360; so Rubio would still be behind even if he won Florida's 99 delegates.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Baumann|first1=Nick|title=Rubio Lost Big. He Has No Realistic Path To Winning Before The GOP Convention.|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/marco-rubio-michigan-mississippi-convention_us_56df8c5ee4b0860f99d72599|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=11 March 2016|date=2016-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ohlemacher|first1=Stephen|title=Rubio Wins Single Delegate as Hawaii Finishes Counting Votes|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/rubio-wins-single-delegate-hawaii-finishes-counting-votes-37567547|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Cillizza|first1=Chris|title=Marco Rubio's Worst Week in Washington|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2016/03/11/marco-rubios-worst-week-in-washington/|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> Also on that day, the Cruz campaign distributed an email indicating that Rubio was being advised to drop out, Rubio responding to the charge denying that he was withdrawing from the race, and his spokesman concluded that Cruz was \"up to his dirty tricks again spreading false rumors and lies.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/2016-gop-primary-live-updates-and-results/2016/03/marco-rubio-ted-cruz-hawaii-dirty-tricks-220423#ixzz42KSgTYML%20|title=Rubio campaign accuses Cruz of 'dirty tricks' in Hawaii|date=March 8, 2016|publisher=Politico}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/marco-rubio-ted-cruz-drop-out-email-hawaii-2016-3|title='Cruz is up to his dirty tricks again': Marco Rubio campaign blasts Ted Cruz in new campaign-trail dustup|first=Allan|last=Smith|date=March 8, 2016|website=Business Insider}}</ref>\n\n=== Florida loss; suspension ===\nIn early March 2016, there became a consensus that Rubio would have to win his home state to remain a credible candidate in the race, political science professor Stephen Craig saying the senator would be \"dead meat\" if he did not win Florida and further questioned if even a victory would be enough to sustain his campaign.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxbusiness.com/politics/2016/03/07/rubio-gambles-on-florida-win-is-it-enough.html|title=Rubio Gambles on Florida Win; Is it Enough?|date=March 7, 2016|first=Elizabeth|last=Chmurak}}</ref> Rubio expressed confidence that he would win Florida.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/2016-gop-primary-live-updates-and-results/2016/03/marco-rubio-florida-primary-2016-220309|title=Rubio vows to win Florida after poor showing on Saturday|date=March 5, 2016|publisher=Politico}}</ref> Rubio's campaign was reported to be aiming for Ohio voters to support Kasich over him to beat Trump, while in contrast describing Rubio as the only candidate able to beat Trump in Florida.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/marco-rubios-campaign-urges-ohio-voters-cast-ballots/story?id=37578597|title=Marco Rubio's Campaign Urges Ohio Voters to Cast Ballots for John Kasich|date=March 11, 2016|publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2016/03/11/marco-rubio-campaign-urges-supporters-to-back-john-kasich-in-ohio/|title=Marco Rubio Aide Urges Supporters to Back|date=March 11, 2016}}</ref> On March 11, CNN averaged six March polls for Florida and found that Rubio was scoring 26% support, less than Trump's 40%.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Agiesta|first1=Jennifer|last2=Scott|first2=Eugene|title=CNN Poll of Polls: Donald Trump leads in Ohio, Florida|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/03/11/politics/cnn-poll-of-polls-ohio-florida/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> Rubio's last rally, the night before the results, was at [[Palm Beach Atlantic University]] in West Palm Beach, FL, just miles from Donald Trump's [[Mar-a-Lago]], where he spoke optimistically of the next day ahead.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wptv.com/news/region-c-palm-beach-county/west-palm-beach/sen-marco-rubio-to-hold-rally-at-palm-beach-atlantic-university-in-west-palm-beach|title=Marco Rubio hosts last rally in West Palm Beach ahead of Florida primary elections|date=March 14, 2016|publisher=WPTV}}</ref> On the day of the Florida primary, Rubio said that his campaign would continue to [[Utah]] regardless of the results and charged the polls, all of which showing him behind Trump, as being \"out of control.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/03/15/politics/marco-rubio-campaign-florida-utah/index.html|title=Marco Rubio vows: I'm going to Utah 'irrespective' of Florida results|date=March 15, 2016|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, 2016, Rubio suspended his campaign, when he finished second in the primary of his home state of [[2016 Florida Republican primary|Florida]] held that day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/16/us/politics/marco-rubio.html|title=Marco Rubio Suspends His Presidential Campaign|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|last2=Barbaro|first2=Michael|date=15 March 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=15 March 2016}}</ref> Rubio won in only 1 ([[Miami-Dade]]) of [[List of counties in Florida|Florida's 67 counties]], and his Florida vote share was 27.0%; Trump won 45.7% and all of Florida's delegates.<ref>{{cite web|title=Florida Primary Results 2016|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/florida|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref> The conclusion of the six March 15 contests (out of which Rubio won none) left Rubio with 169 delegates on the race to reach 1237, but Ted Cruz already had 411 and Trump 673.<ref name=NYTdelegates>{{cite web |last1=Andrews |first1=Wilson |last2=Bennett |first2=Kitty |last3=Parlapiano |first3=Alicia |title=2016 Primary Results and Delegate Count |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/us/elections/primary-calendar-and-results.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=16 March 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316022825/http://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/us/elections/primary-calendar-and-results.html |archivedate=16 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Witcover|first1=Jules|title=The 2016 field narrows, on one side anyway|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/opinion/bal-the-2016-field-narrows-on-one-side-anyway-20160317-story.html|newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|accessdate=1 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Fundraising==\nA [[Super PAC]] in support of Rubio, Conservative Solutions PAC, was launched in the beginning of April 2015. It is led by Warren Tompkins.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2015/04/15/rubio-off-to-fast-fundraising-start-planning-aggressive-florida-schedule/ Marco Rubio gets a super PAC] Washington Post. April 9, 2015.</ref> Miami businessman [[Norman Braman]] was named by political commentators as a probable large donor.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/marco-rubio-hopes-theres-still-enough-money-for-his-own-2016-campaign/2015/03/05/7de9256e-c2a2-11e4-9ec2-b418f57a4a99_story.html Wealthy fans could lift Marco Rubio in 2016] Washington Post. March 5, 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Marco Rubio's secret weapon|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/04/marco-rubio-2016-campaign-norman-braman-117134.html?hp=t1_r|publisher=Politico|accessdate=April 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRubio raised about $1.25 million online the day after his announcement.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2015/04/15/rubio-off-to-fast-fundraising-start-planning-aggressive-florida-schedule/ Rubio, off to fast fundraising start, planning aggressive Florida schedule] Washington Post. April 15, 2015.</ref> By the three-month mark of his campaign \u2013 July 13 \u2013 Rubio had raised over $12 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://marcorubio.com/news/thanks-to-your-support/|title=Thanks to your support...|work=Marco Rubio|accessdate=July 19, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714122323/https://marcorubio.com/news/thanks-to-your-support/|archive-date=July 14, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Between July and September, Rubio acquired $5.7 million for the campaign, noted by [[ABC News]] as being less than the garnered finances of rivals [[Ted Cruz]], [[Carly Fiorina]] and [[Ben Carson]], the latter having triple of Rubio's total.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/marco-rubios-fundraising-goals-fall-short-expectations/story?id=34581331|title=Marco Rubio's Fundraising Numbers Fall Short of Expectations|publisher=ABC News|date=October 19, 2015}}</ref> By [[Christmas]] Rubio raised a total of $47,713,472. It was reported in January that Rubio was canceling a fundraiser to attend a senate meeting, one reportedly having to do with the current affairs of [[North Korea]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/4176097/marco-rubio-attendance-record-votes/|title=Marco Rubio Cancels Fundraiser to Blunt No-Show Attacks|date=January 11, 2016|magazine=TIME}}</ref> That month, Rubio raised roughly $5 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/607423/jeb-bushs-donors-are-already-turning-marco-rubio|title=Jeb Bush's donors are already turning to Marco Rubio|date=February 21, 2016|publisher=theweek.com}}</ref> On March 16, the day after Rubio announced the suspension of his campaign, he met with donors, summarizing the end of the campaign, \"We had a great season but we didn\u2019t get to the [[Super Bowl]] and we didn\u2019t win the Super Bowl\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/03/16/marco-rubio-tells-donors-we-had-a-great-season/|title=Marco Rubio tells donors: 'We had a great season'|date=March 16, 2016|newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n==Endorsements==\n{{see also|Endorsements for the Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016}}\n\n{{hidden begin\n|title=Marco Rubio endorsements\n|titlestyle= background:#B0CEFF; text-align:center;\n}}\n;U.S. Governors (current and former)\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|* [[Robert List]], [[Governor of Nevada|Nevada]] (former)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/2015/oct/04/former-nevada-gov-bob-list-endorses-marco-rubio/|date=October 4, 2015 |title=Former Nevada Gov. Bob List endorses Marco Rubio|work=Las Vegas Sun}}</ref> (previously endorsed Scott Walker)<ref>{{cite web|author=John McCormick |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2015-08-11/scott-walker-wins-former-nevada-governor-s-backing-ahead-of-visit |title=Scott Walker Wins Former Nevada Governor's Backing Ahead of Visit - Bloomberg Politics |website=Bloomberg.com |date=2015-08-11 |accessdate=2016-02-24}}</ref>\n* [[George Pataki]], [[Governor of New York|New York]] (former); [[2016 United States presidential election|2016]] [[George Pataki presidential campaign, 2016|presidential candidate]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaite.com/tv/former-gop-candidate-george-pataki-announces-his-official-2016-endorsement/|title=Former GOP Candidate George Pataki Announces His Official 2016 Endorsement|work=Mediaite|date=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Bobby Jindal]], [[Governor of Louisiana|Louisiana]] (former); [[2016 United States presidential election|2016]] [[Bobby Jindal presidential campaign, 2016|presidential candidate]]<ref>{{cite news|url= http://time.com/4210519/bobby-jindal-marco-rubio-republican/|title=Bobby Jindal Endorses Marco Rubio|work=Mediaite|date=February 4, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Tim Pawlenty]], [[Governor of Minnesota|Minnesota]] (former); 2012 Presidential Candidate<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/2016-gop-primary-live-updates-and-results/2016/02/tim-pawlenty-endorses-marco-rubio-219602|title=Tim Pawlenty endorses Marco Rubio|work=Politico|date=February 22, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[George Allen (U.S. politician)|George Allen]], [[Governor of Virginia|Virginia]] (former Governor and Senator)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bearingdrift.com/2016/01/14/former-governor-george-allen-endorses-marco-rubio/|date=January 14, 2016|title=FORMER GOVERNOR GEORGE ALLEN ENDORSES MARCO RUBIO|work=Bearing Drift}}</ref>\n* [[Scott McCallum]], [[Governor of Wisconsin|Wisconsin]] (former)<ref name=\"marcowiska\">{{cite news|url=http://www.jsonline.com/blogs/news/367147021.html|date=January 31, 2016|title=Ex-governor McCallum endorses Rubio|work=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel}}</ref>\n* [[Craig Benson]], [[Governor of New Hampshire|New Hampshire]] (former)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/marco-rubio-looks-for-strong-new-hampshire-finish/article/2582590|date=February 5, 2016|title=Marco Rubio looks for strong New Hampshire finish|work=The Washington Examiner}}</ref>\n* [[Sam Brownback]], [[Governor of Kansas|Kansas]]<ref>{{cite web|title = Sam Brownback endorses Marco Rubio|url = http://www.kansascity.com/news/local/news-columns-blogs/the-buzz/article60470866.html|website = kansascity|access-date = 2016-02-15}}</ref>\n* [[Nikki Haley]], [[Governor of South Carolina|South Carolina]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/02/breaking-news-south-carolina-gov-nikki-haley-to-endorse-marco-rubio-219390|date=February 17, 2016|title=South Carolina Gov. Nikki Haley endorses Marco Rubio|work=The Washington Examiner}}</ref>\n* [[Asa Hutchinson]], [[Governor of Arkansas|Arkansas]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.star-telegram.com/news/politics-government/national-politics/article61779052.html|title=Arkansas Gov. Asa Hutchinson backs Rubio's presidential bid|work=Star-Telegram.com|date=February 22, 2016}}</ref> (previously endorsed Mike Huckabee)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mikehuckabee.com/news?ID=7A31E413-2B2A-444D-8583-3C75ABAA4C8A |title=Huckabee announces Arkansas leadership team - News and Blog - Mike Huckabee for President |website=Mikehuckabee.com |date=2015-09-28 |accessdate=2016-02-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224092023/http://www.mikehuckabee.com/news?ID=7A31E413-2B2A-444D-8583-3C75ABAA4C8A |archive-date=2016-02-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Luis Fortu\u00f1o]], [[Governor of Puerto Rico|Puerto Rico]] (former)<ref name=\"marcopr\">{{cite news|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/noticias/politica/nota/rubioaseguratresdelos23delegadosdepuertorico-2165505/|date=February 23, 2016|title=Rubio asegura tres de los 23 delegados de Puerto Rico|work=El Nuevo D\u00eda}}</ref>\n* [[Frank Keating]], [[Governor of Oklahoma|Oklahoma]] (former)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.4president.org/2016/2016/02/former-oklahoma-governor-frank-keating-endorses-marco-rubio-for-president.html|title=Former Oklahoma Governor Frank Keating Endorses Marco Rubio For President|work=Blog.4president.org|date=February 23, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Bill Haslam]], [[Governor of Tennessee|Tennessee]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knoxnews.com/news/politics/tennessee-gov-bill-haslam-endorses-marco-rubio-370113471.html|title=Tennessee Gov. Bill Haslam endorses Marco Rubio for GOP presidential nomination|work=Knoxville News Sentinel|date=February 25, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Susana Martinez]], [[Governor of New Mexico|New Mexico]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/03/susana-martinez-endorses-marco-rubio-220166#ixzz41q1J405n|title=N.M. Gov. Susana Martinez to endorse Rubio|work=Politico|date=March 3, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n;U.S. Senators (current and former)\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* Arizona: [[Jon Kyl]] (former)<ref>{{cite web|title = Former Sen. Jon Kyl endorses Marco Rubio for president|url = https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/azdc/2016/01/26/former-sen-jon-kyl-endorses-marco-rubio-president/79322026/|website = azcentral|access-date = 2016-01-26}}</ref> and [[Jeff Flake]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc15.com/news/state/arizona-sen-jeff-flake-endorses-marco-rubio-for-president|title=Arizona Sen. Jeff Flake endorses Marco Rubio for president|work=ABC15 Arizona|date=February 22, 2016}}</ref>\n* Arkansas: [[Tim Hutchinson]] (former)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/politics-government/article54266370.html|title=Former US Sen. Tim Hutchinson backing Rubio for president|work=The News & Observer|date=January 12, 2016}}</ref>\n* Colorado: [[Cory Gardner]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/11/cory-gardner-marco-rubio-215440 |title=Cory Gardner endorses Marco Rubio for president |publisher=Politico |date=November 2, 2015}}</ref>\n* Florida: [[Connie Mack III]] (former)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/the-buzz-florida-politics/former-sen-connie-mack-endorses-marco-rubio/2267324|title=Former Sen. Connie Mack endorses Marco Rubio|work=Tampa Bay Times|date=February 29, 2016}}</ref> and [[Mel Mart\u00ednez]] (former)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://miamiherald.typepad.com/nakedpolitics/2016/02/former-florida-sen-mel-martinez-endorses-marco-rubio.html|title=Former Florida Sen. Mel Martinez endorses Marco Rubio|work=miamiherald.typepad.com|date=February 29, 2016}}</ref>\n* Idaho: [[Jim Risch]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.idahostatesman.com/news/state/idaho/article42973149.html |title=Marco Rubio wins Risch's endorsement |newspaper=Idaho Statesman |date= November 4, 2015}}</ref>\n* Indiana: [[Dan Coats]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Marco Rubio gets endorsement from Sen. Dan Coats|url=http://cbs4indy.com/2016/02/22/marco-rubio-gets-endorsement-from-sen-dan-coats/|accessdate=23 February 2016}}</ref>\n* Kansas: [[Pat Roberts]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cjonline.com/news/2016-02-18/sen-pat-roberts-supports-marco-rubio-calls-gop-debates-weekly-cage-fights|title=Sen. Pat Roberts supports Marco Rubio, calls GOP debates 'weekly cage fights'|work=The Topeka Capital-Journal|date=February 18, 2016}}</ref> [[Bob Dole]] (former, 1996 presidential nominee)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/exclusive-bob-dole-endorses-marco-rubio-2016-race/story?id=37117597 |title=Exclusive: Bob Dole Endorses Marco Rubio in 2016 Race |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=2016-02-19 |accessdate=2016-02-24}}</ref> (previously endorsed Jeb Bush)<ref>{{cite web|last=Green |first=Michael |u